    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ufKXzcvbRBWp"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4. Word2Vec Embeddings\n",
        "\n",
        "### Preparing the Input Data\n",
        "\n",
        "Word2Vec requires each document to be represented as a sequence of tokens. Since the preprocessing stage already generated tokenized reviews, no additional tokenization was required.\n",
        "\n",
        "The existing token arrays are converted into standard Python lists, providing the format expected by the Word2Vec implementation while preserving the original preprocessing performed during the previous stage of the project."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "czzjwMSeG-tD"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Preparing the tokenized reviews for Word2Vec training\n",
        "# Punctuation tokens are removed to focus the model on meaningful words.\n",
        "sentences = df_nonlem[\"tokens\"].apply(\n",
        "    lambda x: [token for token in x.tolist() if token.isalpha()]\n",
        ").tolist()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "x9UrX1VTRsO7"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4.1 Training the Word2Vec Model\n",
        "\n",
        "The Word2Vec model is trained using the **Skip-gram** architecture, which learns vector representations by predicting surrounding words from a target word. Skip-gram is particularly effective for learning semantic relationships, especially in large text corpora.\n",
        "\n",
        "The following parameters were selected:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **`vector_size=100`**: Each word is represented by a 100-dimensional dense vector, providing a balance between expressive power and computational efficiency.\n",
        "- **`window=5`**: Considers five words before and after the target word, allowing the model to capture meaningful contextual information.\n",
        "- **`min_count=5`**: Removes very rare words that may correspond to typographical errors or noisy observations.\n",
        "- **`sg=1`**: Uses the Skip-gram architecture instead of CBOW, improving semantic similarity learning.\n",
        "- **`epochs=5`**: Trains the model over five iterations of the corpus, allowing the embeddings to converge while maintaining reasonable training time."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "XN6ZGCL7He57",
        "outputId": "bd385c1d-38ff-4e78-a07a-92a7f2697b02"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Vocabulary size: 29,419\n",
            "Embedding dimension: 100\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Train the Word2Vec model\n",
        "w2v_model = Word2Vec(\n",
        "    sentences=sentences,\n",
        "    vector_size=100,\n",
        "    window=5,\n",
        "    min_count=5,\n",
        "    workers=4,\n",
        "    sg=1,\n",
        "    epochs=5\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Vocabulary size: {len(w2v_model.wv):,}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Embedding dimension: {w2v_model.vector_size}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "vfS0y1njR0u7"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Results\n",
        "\n",
        "The trained model learned vector representations for **29,419 unique words**. Each word is represented by a **100-dimensional embedding**, enabling semantic similarity analysis and visualization of relationships between medical concepts.\n",
        "The Gensim implementation of Word2Vec was used because it provides an efficient and widely adopted framework for learning distributed word representations.\""
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "oOTLbLcGSLrb"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4.2 Semantic Similarity Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "One of the main advantages of Word2Vec is its ability to capture semantic relationships between words.\n",
        "\n",
        "Using the learned embeddings, the model can identify words that frequently occur in similar contexts. This provides insight into the semantic structure of the corpus and demonstrates that the model has successfully learned meaningful representations from the drug reviews."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "AH17YY_kHi6F"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def show_similar_words(word, topn=10):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Display the most semantically similar words for a given query term.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    print(\"=\" * 60)\n",
        "    print(f\"Query word: '{word}'\\n\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    if word in w2v_model.wv:\n",
        "        similar_words = w2v_model.wv.most_similar(word, topn=topn)\n",
        "\n",
        "        print(f\"{'Similar Word':<20}{'Similarity Score'}\")\n",
        "        print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
        "\n",
        "        for similar_word, score in similar_words:\n",
        "            print(f\"{similar_word:<20}{score:.4f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        print(f\"'{word}' was not found in the vocabulary.\")"
      ]
    },
